NEW WASHINGTON HOTEL
SEATTLE
Jan.26,1933.
Dear Debby;
This letter to you is for me what Hoboken is for the
Theatrical producers - I am trying out my
skill on the Corona.
Looks pretty good so far no est pas!
I was very lucky it seems to get through to Portland
by air,as no ships came over the route from Salt lake either be-
fore or since within a twenty four hour period. The weather was
perfect when we came except for a few snow storms. The trip down
the Columbia River Canyon was beautiful or rather it was grand.
Great snow covered mountains towering above us on either side
with the water down below boiling and
churning over the rocks
and down the rapids. The sun was setting right in front
of us
behind a mountain of clouds rising thousands of feet into the
sky. Later as we got down toward where the River broadens out
to a mile or more the sun had gone down and the lightd of Van-
couver, Washington showed on our left. Farbher on to the right
other little
town lights twinkled and then as we passed over
the river and headed slightly Southwest we
could see the red
Neon sign of the Richfield Oil Co. It is on top of a tall off-
